m/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f76d17976d6b2c69167c10a1a18ad57e365c59be.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40b20273217e1b18c59bbcd3f48b6ecca758706c.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed778e8997d71cec69276a0a32dbb603eb48ffc9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/45a3d4a0cf7fba317fc285700037318d60dfa27d.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0f1453d113f15d43bcedff19610229a7f75ebf60.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6708d8959440b8805afc8470858dfedc048bcaa7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5a0098f13086eababf4f3999ed7201d14098ef6a.jpeg"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" a checkbox for \u0022Create GIT repository,\u0022 which is checked. The UI is designed to facilitate project setup, indicating that the user can specify a model location and optionally initialize a GIT repository for version control. In addition, there is a back navigation arrow labeled \u0022New Project\u0022 at the top left.\n\n\n  \n In this case, an invisible  .git  directory is created in your project folder. This is where all Git\u2019s internal data is stored. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7605661211bed480b465b8b8647607f85d484aeb.png]\nDescription: The image displays a file directory structure on a Windows PC. The path shown is \u0022This PC \u003E Local Disk (C:) \u003E OrigamProjects \u003E TaskManager.\u0022 The visible content includes a list of folders with the following names: \u0022.git,\u0022 \u0022customAssets,\u0022 \u0022Docker,\u0022 \u0022l10n,\u0022 and \u0022model.\u0022 Each folder is associated with a modification date of \u00221/13/2025\u0022 at various times, with the \u0022.git\u0022 folder modified last at \u00224:24 PM.\u0022 All items listed are categorized as \u0022File folder.\u0022 The apparent purpose is to organize project-related files for the TaskManager component of the OrigamProjects.\n\n\n  \n   Git setup \n When creating a new project, and if you enable the automatic creation of a new Git repository in the wizard, the system will also configure Git for you and set up your name and email. If you are setting up Git manually, you will need to use the  git config  command or use the Settings in TortoiseGit. \n The most important thing is to have your name and email set up. However, if you are working on your application alone, these settings are not absolutely crucial. \n \n \nGit Bash \n To view the configuration in Git Bash, use this command: \n  git config --list\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/bd9c977144367ec26ee179644e1cc915e2783828.png]\nDescription: The image displays a terminal window showing the output of the command \u0060git config --list\u0060, which lists the Git configuration settings for the current user and repository. The visible UI text includes various configuration entries such as \u0060diff.astextplain.textconv=astextplain\u0060, \u0060filter.lfs.clean=git-lfs clean -- %f\u0060, and \u0060credential.helper=manager\u0060. Other notable configurations include email settings, repository versions, and SSL certificate paths. The purpose of this output is to provide an overview of the current Git configurations, useful for debugging or reviewing settings in a Git-managed project.\n\n\n  \n \n \n \nTortoiseGit \n Here\u2019s what the configuration looks like in TortoiseGit when using the  Settings  option: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f75b7f2fa6f3220960d1832552cae6811de975f5.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a settings window for TortoiseGit, specifically configured under the \u0022Git\u0022 section of \u0022Settings.\u0022 On the left panel, various categories are listed, including \u0022General,\u0022 \u0022Git,\u0022 \u0022Credential,\u0022 \u0022Hook Scripts,\u0022 and more, with icons indicating their functions. The main area shows configuration options such as \u0022Config source\u0022 with radio buttons for selecting \u0022Effective,\u0022 \u0022Local,\u0022 \u0022Global,\u0022 and \u0022System.\u0022 User Information fields include \u0022User Name,\u0022 \u0022Email,\u0022 and \u0022Signing key ID,\u0022 each with an \u0022inherit\u0022 checkbox. There are settings for \u0022Auto CrLf convert,\u0022 displaying dropdowns for configuration options \u0022AutoCrLf\u0022 (set to true) and \u0022SafeCrLf.\u0022 Below, buttons are provided to \u0022Edit local .git/config,\u0022 \u0022Edit global .gitconfig,\u0022 \u0022Edit .tigconfig,\u0022 and \u0022View effective config.\u0022 The layout is designed for managing Git settings effectively within the TortoiseGit interface.\n\n\n  \n \n   Initial version \n If you let the wizard create the Git repository for you, the initial version of your application is automatically created as well. If not, you will need to use the command  git init . \n Git is associated with your ORIGAM project folder, which, for example, can be found at  C:\\OrigamProjects\\MyApplication . This assumes that you are using the default folder  C:\\OrigamProjects\\  and that your application is named  MyApplication . If you have named any of these differently, the path to your project folder will naturally differ. \n Now, let\u2019s check the initial version. \n \n \nGitBash \n To verify the initial commit, navigate to the directory where your project is located, for example, by using this command: \n  cd /c/OrigamProjects/MyApplication/\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:39:11"},"vector":[-0.03558292,0.011195207,-0.054249194,0.04948765,0.021642998,-0.01267939,-0.001163064,-0.025291415,0.0020253104,0.033093575,0.018852416,-0.026195407,-0.02611646,0.013578618,0.0061515854,-0.028587